observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous recommendations that the City Mayor direct the City Accountant and City Treasurer to:
a. stop granting cash advances to officials, employees or accountable officers (AOs) with outstanding cash advances, and to strictly monitor the granting and utilization of cash advances;
b. prepare follow-up demand letters to all AOs with unliquidated cash advances including those AOs who have retired or already out of service;
c. initiate disciplinary actions against those officials responsible for the disbursements not covered with Liquidation Reports and/or without complete documentations; and
d. require the Accountant to cause the refund of the total amount of cash advance which were not covered with Liquidation Reports and not duly documented.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
- City Accountant to:
  a. not to process the payments for Disbursement Vouchers (DVs) with incomplete supporting documents;
  b. record purchases of supplies as debit to the appropriate asset account using the Perpetual Inventory Method regardless of whether or not they were consumed within the accounting period;
  c. maintain the Subsidiary Ledger Cards for each type of supplies and materials; and
  d. record the issuances based on the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) instead of the Request and Issue Slip (RIS);
- City General Services Officer (CGSO) and other concerned personnel to:
  a. maintain Stock Cards for supplies; b. prepare and submit monthly the SSMI to the City Accountant for the recording of issuances; and c. prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to report the physical count of supplies by type of inventory as of a given date.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the City Mayor:
a. require the City Accountant to explain why procurement through reimbursement basis was still allowed;
b. instruct the City Accountant to stop processing DVs through reimbursement and instead settle obligations by drawing checks payable to suppliers;
c. direct the concerned officials to further improve their measures to minimize, if not eliminate, these disbursements paid thru reimbursement basis as regular and recurring expenses should not be paid through reimbursement basis to comply with the stated provisions of law aside from ensuring that the National Treasury receive the mandatory tax collections from business enterprises; and
d. instruct the City Accountant to submit to the Audit Team all the lacking documents needed to support the disbursements.

We recommended that the City Mayor and other concerned officials:
• review and study the current plantilla position to come up with a more realistic organizational structure for the City;
• limit the hiring of casuals and JOs to those that are extremely necessary according to the immediate and actual needs of each Office, with consideration on the financial capability of the City government;
• fill-up the vacant plantilla position and hire qualified individuals who will provide the regular services provided in the City; and
• submit justifications on the necessity of hiring JO personnel for evaluation of the Audit Team.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the City Mayor and other concerned City officials:
abide by the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR on the procurement of consulting services and adopt written policy/procedure/guidelines in hiring consultants to ensure that only the services of individuals who have technical and professional expertise on the types of projects or activities needed by the City would be availed of;
reassess the need of hiring consultants and determine their capabilities based on proven expertise, experience and capability to avoid unnecessary and excessive expenditures;
prepare the Terms of Reference (TOR) and consider whether there is no duplication of functions in the hiring of consultants;
evaluate and streamline the current roster of consultants and discontinue renewing consultants with redundant responsibilities to prevent unnecessary and excessive expenditures;
perform periodic monitoring/oversight in the use of consultants to determine the extent to which economy, efficiency and effectiveness have been achieved; and
strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 and immediately submit the required supporting documents, including accomplishment reports, in the payments of honoraria of consultants and justifications on the necessity of hiring consultants for evaluation.

We reiterated our recommendation that the City Mayor direct:
• the concerned officials to demand payment of liquidated damages from erring contractors to avoid disallowance in audit and consequently conduct thorough monitoring of their implementation of projects and be aware of delays for which liquidated damages due the City Government can be claimed;
• the City Engineering Office to ensure that projects are completed within the contract time to avoid delays resulting in deferred benefits to the public apart from the incurrence of liquidated damages;
• the City Accountant to ensure the submission of guarantee instruments in the advance payment and posting of warranty security in the payment of infrastructure projects by the contractors; and
• the concerned officials to submit to the Audit Team the lacking documents supporting the procurement for the evaluation of the same to avoid audit suspensions and disallowances.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:
• the City Accountant to implement strictly the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances. Strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents;
• the concerned Accountable Officers to immediately liquidate their outstanding cash advances and the City Accountant to send final demand letters to persons who have retired or out of service who still have unliquidated cash advances; and
• the City Accountant to enforce withholding of salaries of accountable officers who fail to effect prompt liquidation of their cash advances. Otherwise, the accountable officers shall be held criminally liable, for failure to settle their accounts;
• the City Accountant to analyze the accounts with abnormal balances and verify the journal entries and the postings made to the involved accounts. Accordingly, make the necessary reconciliation and adjustments/corrections in the books for those accounts with negative balances included under the outstanding cash advances as of December 31, 2015. Also, effect the necessary adjustment for the ₱19.70 discrepancy noted between the Statement of Financial Position balance and schedule of Advances to Officers and Employees account.
We further reiterated the previous years’ audit recommendation on the filing of appropriate cases/charges against accountable officers with outstanding cash advances from previous years. In the case of the cash advances involving intelligence/confidential funds, we recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Accountant to follow up the submitted liquidation reports in the Commission on Audit - Intelligence and Confidential Fund Audit Unit (COA-ICFAU).

We recommended that the City Mayor and other concerned City officials:
• abide by the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR on the procurement of consulting services and adopt written policy/procedure/guidelines in hiring consultants to ensure that only the services of individuals who have technical and professional expertise on the types of projects or activities needed by the City would be availed of;
• ensure adequate planning for hiring of consultants by conducting an assessment whether the services are beyond the in-house capability of the City;
• include consultancy projects in the APP, prepare the Terms of Reference and consider whether there is no duplication of functions in hiring of consultants;
• evaluate and streamline the current roster of consultants and discontinue renewing consultants with redundant responsibilities to prevent unnecessary and excessive expenditures;
• perform periodic monitoring/oversight in the use of consultants to determine the extent to which economy, efficiency and effectiveness have been achieved; and
• strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 and immediately submit the required supporting documents, including accomplishment reports, in the payments of honoraria of consultants and justifications on the necessity of hiring consultants for evaluation.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the concerned officials to strictly comply with all other prescribed procedures and guidelines under RA No. 9003 and strictly continue and enforce all its City Ordinances specifically related in environmental compliance to ensure proper waste segregation, thorough collection of wastes based on set schedules and reduction of wastes.
Likewise, establish government-owned MRFs as required under RA No. 9003 and encourage all the Barangays to do the same and promote and support the SWM programs of the City.
We recommended that the City Mayor require the City Solid Waste Management Board (CSWMB) to formulate and to implement an adequate monitoring system that would ensure that all activities contracted are effectively and efficiently discharged. The monitoring system should also include the establishment of adequate performance indicators/standards from which performance of contractor could be measured.
Specifically, we recommended that the City Mayor direct the CSWMB and City ENRO to:
- establish policies and procedures on monitoring including setting parameters/indicators to assess the performance of the contractor. These indicators should be clearly stated in the contract and closely monitored to ensure delivery of satisfactory services;
- identify the major activities to be monitored and establish strategies to monitor each activity;
- establish a representative percentage for each activity to be monitored and assign monitors in specific areas that they could possibly cover within the day to ensure that the reports could be used as a valid basis in assessing the performance of contractors;
- define the activities to be monitored, the items to be reported and the records to be maintained;
- establish feedback mechanism where constituents/residents could report their complaints on unsatisfactory performance of the contractors such as complaint hotlines or regular surveys, to determine public satisfaction on the performance of the contractors; and
- monitor the actions taken on valid complaints received from the residents by maintaining a logbook indicating the time the complaint was received, the complaining party and the contact number, the specific place being complained of, the nature of the complaint, the person receiving the complaint, the time the said complaint was relayed to the contractor and the action taken by the contractor. The actions taken by the contractor can be established by requiring the complaining party to inform the City on the actions taken by the contractor and the specific time such actions were taken or by sending a monitor to validate the contractor's action; and strictly require the proper filling up of the Delivery Receipts.

